1) MHD_is_feature_supported — print_perf_warnings calls this function conditionally. To determine whether print_perf_warnings (or code it invokes) violates the MISRA rule you must inspect the implementation of MHD_is_feature_supported to see whether it calls memcmp to compare null‑terminated strings (or otherwise performs forbidden string comparisons with memcmp). If MHD_is_feature_supported uses memcmp on C strings, that would make the call chain from print_perf_warnings relevant to the MISRA violation.

2) memcmp — the MISRA rule concerns uses of the standard memcmp function. Include memcmp as a symbol so the analyzer can locate all call sites and examine argument usage (are the operands null‑terminated C strings or raw memory buffers, and is strlen/explicit length used). Even though memcmp is a library routine, you must identify its usages in the reachable code (particularly in MHD_is_feature_supported) to decide whether the rule is violated.
